05866nam a22006855i 9780674985278DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20182018mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806749852787 a10.4159/97806749852782doi  a(DE-B1597)501468  a(OCoLC)1027787332  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aJA81b.M3285 2018eb 7aPOL0100002bisacsh04a320.092231 aKapossy, Béla, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMarkets, Morals, Politics :bJealousy of Trade and the History of Political Thought /cBéla Kapossy. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. Marx and Material Culture: Istvan Hont and the History of Scholarship -- t2. Sociability in Sacred Historical Perspective, 1650–1800 -- t3. From Rousseau to Kant -- t4. Modern Representative Democracy: Intellectual Genealogy and Drawbacks -- t5. Revision, Reorganization, and Reform: Prussia, 1790–1820 -- t6. Liberty, Autonomy, and Republican Historiography: Civic Humanism in Context -- t7. Millennium and Enlightenment: Robert Owen and the Second Coming of the Truth -- t8. Identification and the Politics of Envy -- t9. Commerce, Credit, and Sovereignty: The Nation-State as Historical Critique -- t10. Why We Need a Global History of Political Thought -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen István Hont died in 2013, the world lost a giant of intellectual history. A leader of the Cambridge School of Political Thought, Hont argued passionately for a global-historical approach to political ideas. To better understand the development of liberalism, he looked not only to the works of great thinkers but also to their reception and use amid revolution and interstate competition. His innovative program of study culminated in the landmark 2005 book Jealousy of Trade, which explores the birth of economic nationalism and other social effects of expanding eighteenth-century markets. Markets, Morals, Politics brings together a celebrated cast of Hont’s contemporaries to assess his influence, ideas, and methods. Richard Tuck, John Pocock, John Dunn, Raymond Geuss, Gareth Stedman Jones, Michael Sonenscher, John Robertson, Keith Tribe, Pasquale Pasquino, and Peter N. Miller contribute original essays on themes Hont treated with penetrating insight: the politics of commerce, debt, and luxury; the morality of markets; and economic limits on state power. The authors delve into questions about the relationship between states and markets, politics and economics, through examinations of key Enlightenment and pre-Enlightenment figures in context—Hobbes, Rousseau, Spinoza, and many others. The contributors also add depth to Hont’s lifelong, if sometimes veiled, engagement with Marx. The result is a work of interpretation that does justice to Hont’s influence while developing its own provocative and illuminating arguments. Markets, Morals, Politics will be a valuable companion to readers of Hont and anyone concerned with political economy and the history of ideas.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCommercexPolitical aspects. 0aPolitical ethics. 0aPolitical sciencexHistory. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh1 aDunn, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeuss, Raymond, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Gareth Stedman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKapossy, Béla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller, Peter N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.go